ack from the crash of1987, other stock markets around the world have made fasterrecoveries than Wall Street.   ``It wasn't that the U.S. did poorly,'' Mark Sladkus, a vicepresident at Morgan Stanley andamp; Co., said Friday. ''It's that theother markets had special circumstances.''</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Though some first-time investors who were scaredaway by the stock market crash two years ago never returned, thosewho remained got their reward, market-watchers say.   The record high of 2,734.64 in the Dow Jones industrials averageThursday once again pointed out the value of a long-term investmentstrategy, these observers said Friday.   Anyone who held stocks for the past two years has about brokeneven, while people who panicked and sold at the bottom took biglosses.</TEXT><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Hundreds of video rental shops have receivedpromotional kits for a horror movie with live snakes inside thepackages, and outraged animal protection officials called the stunt``cruel and irresponsible.''   The Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals calledon Cinema International Corp. on Friday to take back the 700reptiles.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two federal agencies and the financialexchanges they regulate are squaring off over a new product forinvestors known as a ``stock basket.''   On one side are the stock exchanges and their overseer, theSecurities and Exchange Commission. On the other is the newerCommodity Futures Trading Commission and its charges, the boisterousmarkets that deal in commodities.   The product at issue is technically called an ``indexparticipation,'' but it resembles a basket of stocks because itallows investors to buy or sell something with a value tied to broadstock market indexes, such as the Standard andamp; Poors 500.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Commercial bankers who successfully kept theirdeposit insurance fund away from failed savings and loans say theSandamp;Ls are engaged in a ``sneaky scheme'' to appropriate the name ofthe Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., which once exclusively belongedto banks.   But James H. Grohl, senior vice president of the U.S. League ofSavings Institutions, isn't worried about the complaints over itsletter saying thrift institutions can advertise they are insured bythe FDIC.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal Reserve policymakers voted to nudgeinterest rates lower in July, but they worried about reignitinginflation by going too far, according to minutes of the meeting.   The Federal Open Market Committee, noting fairly consistentweakness in housing and consumer spending, voted 10-1 at the end ofits July 5-6 meeting to lower short-term interest rates, accordingto the minutes released Friday.   Subsequently, the benchmark federal funds rate _ the rate bankscharge each other for overnight loans _ fell twice, in quarter-pointincrements, to 9 percent.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Stock prices posted a small loss Friday, hesitating after theyearlong rally that carried the market to record highs Thursday. TheDow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped back 2.28 to 2,732.36.   The dollar finished higher in domestic dealings after decliningoverseas. Bond prices dropped after a selloff in Treasury issues.   Cocoa futures prices plunged as traders looked ahead to nextmonth's meeting of the International Cocoa Organization with anexpectation of failure. Copper prices reached new contract highs,grain and soybean futures plunged, precious metals declined, oilfutures were down and livestock and meat futures were mixed.</TEXT></DOC>